    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Sarcocornia littorea</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_9752",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Erect, perennial, succulent shrub found close to the high-water mark on rocky shores. Usually with thick woody stems (remains of dead stems often present around base of clumps). Main stems bearing lateral branches covered in succulent bead-like segments, terminal segments rounded knobs. Leaves minute and difficult to observe and tiny white flowers emerge from terminal segments of stems, usually in groups of three. Tips of branches often orange to red.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9753",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically reach a height of 80-100 cm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9754",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Orange River to about Algoa Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9755",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Salt-tolerant plant that occurs low on rocky shores, almost down to the high water mark<i>. </i>Usually erect, but can dangle form crevices, although tips of branches usually turn upwards<i>.</i></p><p>Species in this genus have a long history of use as food plants in Europe and can be eaten raw in salads, pickled, or cooked as a vegetable.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9756",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9757",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Members of this genus are typically wind pollinated and produce small seeds which are dispersed by wind or water.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9758",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This genus contains several other local species. This species is most likely to be confused with <i>S. littorea</i> is <i>S. pillani</i>, which forms similar largeish shrubs just above the driftline on but in salt marshes. Several other species are also found on soft substrate in the upper intertidal zone of saltmarshes and estuaries. These include the taller bushy Marsh samphire <i>S. wayeriana</i> which has succulent rather than woody stems and several shorter species which form creeping underground runners and send up numerous short vertical stems to create a ‘lawn’.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9759",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
